article.description: Seattle's Ray Allen scored a season-high 42 points to help the Sonics overcome a 23-point deficit and defeat the Blazers on Monday night.
article.headline: Allen scores season-high 42 points
article.linkText: Sonics overcome 23-point deficit to beat Blazers
article.story:
SEATTLE (AP) -- Ray Allen is living up to his nickname. Seattle's star guard scored a season-high 42 points, and helped the SuperSonics overcome a 23-point deficit in a 119-108 overtime win against the Portland Trail Blazers on Monday night. Allen helped the Sonics come back by scoring 20 points in the fourth quarter and another seven in overtime. The Blazers led 87-69 after the third quarter, but completely collapsed and had no answer for Allen. "He went off in the fourth quarter," Portland's Zach Randolph said. "That's why I call him Big Play Ray." Vladimir Radmanovic was 5-for-8 from 3-point range and finished with 21 points. Reserve Antonio Daniels scored 12 for Seattle and Calvin Booth came off the bench to score 11. But it was Allen who put on a show while helping the Sonics outscore the Blazers 35-17 in the fourth quarter and then 15-4 in overtime. Jerome James added five of his 11 points in the extra period. "They just looked like a deer in the headlights," Allen said of the Blazers in the fourth quarter. "We just kept hitting them so hard and they didn't have an answer for any of it." Allen, in only his seventh game back after 25 games on the injured list after having bone spurs removed from his right ankle, was unstoppable. He was 16-for-27 from the field, dished out eight assists, and pulled down six rebounds. Allen had given the Sonics a 104-102 lead when he hit a 3-pointer with 19.7 seconds left, but Damon Stoudamire sent the game into overtime with a 22-footer with 1.1 seconds left. "I thought we had regained the momentum with Damon's shot," Dale Davis said, "but in the end we still didn't have an answer for Ray Allen." Randolph led Portland with 28 points. He scored 19 of them in the first half. Stoudamire added 22. Davis had 15, Wesley Person came off the bench for 14, and Jeff McInnis added 12 for the Blazers, who have lost four out of five. The Blazers are now 1-12 on the road. They came into the game having won 14 of their previous 18 games at Seattle. "Unbelievable," Blazers coach Maurice Cheeks said. "They missed a lot of shots early on and we fast broke and got a lot of open baskets for ourselves. Then we started missing in the fourth quarter. Of course, Ray Allen had an unbelievable game." Davis echoed his coach's disbelief. "Allen definitely was a big key to their win," Davis said. "Time after time he made big shots. When a guy get in a zone like that, with his ability, you can't stop him." The game wasn't close for the first three quarters. Portland led by 12 at the end of the first quarter, 19 at the half, and 18 at the end of the third. The Blazers were dominant inside during the first half, when they outrebounded the Sonics 29-10 on their way to a 64-45 halftime lead. "It was two different basketball games," Sonics coach Nate McMillan said. "For us to come back the way we did, that is a credit to those guys. This team surprised me."

Game notes
The Blazers signed C Slavko Vranes to a 10-day contract. The 7-foot-5 Vranes replaces F Travis Outlaw, who was placed on the injured list with tendinitis in his knee. Vranes had been on the injured list before being waived by the New York Knicks on Dec. 24. ... In the second quarter, Person outrebounded the entire Sonics team 6-2. ... The Sonics, who lost to Sacramento by 31 points Sunday, are now 6-2 in the second game of back-to-backs. They are 2-6 in the first games.
